📄 MongoDB Helm Deployment – Detailed Troubleshooting Report
1️⃣ Environment Overview
Infrastructure

AWS EC2

Kubernetes Cluster

Worker Nodes

Custom Helm Chart

StatefulSet for MongoDB

NodePort Service

Manual PersistentVolume (hostPath)

Initial MongoDB Version
mongo:4.0.8
2️⃣ Issue 1 – Mongosh Compatibility Error
❌ Error Observed
MongoServerSelectionError:
Server reports maximum wire version 7,
but Node.js Driver requires at least 8 (MongoDB 4.2)
🔍 Technical Analysis

Wire version mapping:

Wire Version	MongoDB Version
7	MongoDB 4.0
8	MongoDB 4.2

Modern mongosh requires MongoDB ≥ 4.2.

Server was running MongoDB 4.0.8.

🛠 Troubleshooting Steps

Checked MongoDB version:

kubectl exec -it mongodb-0 -- mongod --version

Confirmed v4.0.8

Identified version mismatch

✅ Resolution

Upgraded image to:

mongo:6.0
3️⃣ Issue 2 – CrashLoopBackOff After Upgrade
❌ Error Observed
This version of MongoDB is too recent to start up on the existing data files.
🔍 Technical Root Cause

MongoDB storage engine = WiredTiger.

Data files created by MongoDB 4.0 existed inside:

/mnt/data

Deployment used:

hostPath:
  path: "/mnt/data"

When upgrading to MongoDB 6/7:

New server tried reading old storage format

Storage engine incompatibility

Pod crashed

4️⃣ Issue 3 – WiredTiger Version Conflict
❌ Error Observed
unsupported WiredTiger file version:
this build only supports versions up to 3,
and the file is version 5
🔍 What Happened

Opposite version conflict occurred:

MongoDB 7 data files existed

Deployment reverted back to mongo:4.0.8

Older server cannot read newer storage files

Result:

Fatal Assertion 28595
CrashLoopBackOff
5️⃣ Deep Storage Troubleshooting
Step 1 – Verify Image Version
kubectl describe pod mongodb-0 | grep Image

Confirmed incorrect image version.

Step 2 – Check PV & PVC
kubectl get pvc
kubectl get pv

Confirmed PV was using hostPath.

Step 3 – Identify Physical Storage Location

PV YAML:

hostPath:
  path: "/mnt/data"

SSH into worker node:

sudo ls /mnt/data

Found old WiredTiger files:

WiredTiger
collection-*.wt
journal/
mongod.lock
Important Learning

Deleting PVC does NOT delete hostPath data.

Because:

persistentVolumeReclaimPolicy: Retain

hostPath stores data directly on node disk.

6️⃣ Final Resolution Steps
Step 1 – Remove Helm Release
helm uninstall mongodb
Step 2 – Delete PV & PVC
kubectl delete pvc mongodb-pvc
kubectl delete pv mongodb-pv
Step 3 – Manually Clean Disk

On worker node:

sudo rm -rf /mnt/data/*
Step 4 – Correct Image Version

Updated StatefulSet:

image: mongo:6.0
Step 5 – Fresh Install
helm install mongodb .
Step 6 – Verification
kubectl get pods
kubectl exec -it mongodb-0 -- mongod --version

Pod successfully moved to:

1/1 Running
